This article presents the '''demographic history of [[Romania]]''' through [[census]] results. See [[Demographics of Romania]] for a more detailed overview of the country's present-day demographics.
The 1930 census was the only one to cover [[Greater Romania]]. Censuses in 1948, 1956, 1966, 1977, 1992, 2002 and 2011 covered Romania's present-day territory.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.recensamantromania.ro/istoric/lista-recensafmintelor-populaaiei/|title= Lista recensămintelor populaţiei din România|year=2011|accessdate=2011-06-03|publisher=Institutul Naţional de Statistică}}</ref> All but the 1948 census, which asked about mother tongue, had a question on ethnicity. [[Moldavia]] and [[Wallachia]] each held a census in 1859. The [[Romanian Old Kingdom]] conducted statistical estimates in 1884, 1889 and 1894, and held censuses in 1899 and 1912. [[Ion Antonescu]]'s regime also held two: a general one in April 1941, and one for those with "[[Jew]]ish blood" in May 1942.
