{{Infobox ethnic group | group = Turks in South Africa | image = | caption = | population = 3,500<ref name=TodaysZaman/> | popplace = {{hlist| [[Cape Town]] | [[Johannesburg]] | [[Pretoria]] }} | langs = [[Turkish language|Turkish]] | rels = [[Islam]] }}
'''Turks in South Africa''' refers to the ethnic [[Turkish people|Turkish]] community living in [[South Africa]].
==History==
===Ottoman Era=== [[Turkish people|Turks]] began immigrating to [[South Africa]] during the 19th century.<ref name="Aydin 2003 loc=1">{{Harvnb|Aydin|2003|loc=1}}.</ref> In 1889, the [[Ottoman Turks]] sent and maintained Honorary Consulates in [[Johannesburg]] and [[Durban]]. By April 1914, [[Mehmet Remzi Bey]] was assigned as Consul General of the [[Ottoman Empire]] to Johannesburg; he died in 1916 and was buried in the Braamfontein cemetery in Johannesburg. On 21 November 2011, his remains were transferred to a memorial garden at the Nizamiye Mosque in Johannesburg.<ref name="Aydin 2003 loc=1"/><ref name=TodaysZaman>{{cite web|author=Today's Zaman|title=Being a Turk in South Africa|url=http://www.todayszaman.com/tz-web/columnists-201638-being-a-turk-in-south-africa.html|accessdate=2010-07-14|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100811090621/http://todayszaman.com/tz-web/columnists-201638-being-a-turk-in-south-africa.html|archivedate=2010-08-11|df=}}</ref>
At the request of the members of the sizeable Muslim community who were living in the [[Cape Colony]], the Ottoman government sent [[Abu Bakr Effendi]] to [[Cape Town]] to teach as well as preach [[Islam]] and help settle religious matters among Muslims. His descendants still live in various parts of South Africa.<ref name="Aydin 2003 loc=1"/>
==Notable people== *[[Tatamkulu Afrika]] *[[Abu Bakr Effendi]]
